

**Phase 1 — Input **
- PS/2 keyboard driver (IRQ1, already have the hook)
- PS/2 mouse driver (IRQ12)

**Phase 2 — Memory manager**
- Physical memory manager (bitmap)
- Virtual memory / paging
- `kmalloc`/`kfree`
- Without this nothing else works

**Phase 3 — Syscalls + ELF**
- Syscall handler (`syscall` instruction, not int 0x80)
- ELF64 loader
- Ring 3 / userspace
- musl-compatible syscalls (this is a big list but doable)

**Phase 4 — Filesystem**
- VFS layer
- initramfs to start
- ext2 or FAT32

**Phase 5 — GCC port**
- Get musl libc compiling against your syscalls
- Then GCC can target your OS
- This unlocks building everything else natively

**Phase 6 — Graphics**
- GOP/UEFI framebuffer (better than VGA for modern GPUs)
- TinyGL on top of framebuffer
- Pick one GPU to target first — virtio-gpu for QEMU, then Intel or AMD

**Phase 7 — Desktop + Browser**
- Desktop environment (needs TinyGL + input drivers)
- Browser last — realistically port NetSurf, writing one from scratch is a multi-year project alone

**Phase 8 — Package manager**
- Can be written in C against your own syscalls once GCC works
- Design the package format before writing the tool


